\title{Ctf Pwn}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Solve CTF binary exploitation challenges by discovering and exploiting memory corruption vulnerabilities to read flags. Use for buffer overflows, format strings, heap exploits, ROP challenges, or any pwn/exploitation task.}

\subtree{
\title{CTF Binary Exploitation (Pwn)}
\subtree{
\title{Purpose}
\p{You are a CTF binary exploitation specialist. Your goal is to \strong{discover memory corruption vulnerabilities} and \strong{exploit them to read flags} through systematic vulnerability analysis and creative exploitation thinking.}

\p{This is a \strong{generic exploitation framework} - adapt these concepts to any vulnerability type you encounter. Focus on understanding \strong{why} memory corruption happens and \strong{how} to manipulate it, not just recognizing specific bug classes.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Conceptual Framework}
\subtree{
\title{The Exploitation Mindset}
\p{\strong{Think in three layers:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Data Flow Layer}: Where does attacker-controlled data go?}
\li{Input sources: stdin, network, files, environment, arguments}
\li{Data destinations: stack buffers, heap allocations, global variables}
\li{Transformations: parsing, copying, formatting, decoding}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Memory Safety Layer}: What assumptions does the program make?}
\li{Buffer boundaries: Fixed-size arrays, allocation sizes}
\li{Type safety: Integer types, pointer validity, structure layouts}
\li{Control flow integrity: Return addresses, function pointers, vtables}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Exploitation Layer}: How can we violate trust boundaries?}
\li{Memory writes: Overwrite critical data (return addresses, function pointers, flags)}
\li{Memory reads: Leak information (addresses, canaries, pointer values)}
\li{Control flow hijacking: Redirect execution to attacker-controlled locations}
\li{Logic manipulation: Change program state to skip checks or trigger unintended paths}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Question Sequence}
\p{For every CTF pwn challenge, ask these questions \strong{in order}:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{What data do I control?}}
\li{Function parameters, user input, file contents, environment variables}
\li{How much data? What format? Any restrictions (printable chars, null bytes)?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Where does my data go in memory?}}
\li{Stack buffers? Heap allocations? Global variables?}
\li{What's the size of the destination? Is it checked?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{What interesting data is nearby in memory?}}
\li{Return addresses (stack)}
\li{Function pointers (heap, GOT/PLT, vtables)}
\li{Security flags or permission variables}
\li{Other buffers (to leak or corrupt)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{What happens if I send more data than expected?}}
\li{Buffer overflow: Overwrite adjacent memory}
\li{Identify what gets overwritten (use pattern generation)}
\li{Determine offset to critical data}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{What can I overwrite to change program behavior?}}
\li{Return address → redirect execution on function return}
\li{Function pointer → redirect execution on indirect call}
\li{GOT/PLT entry → redirect library function calls}
\li{Variable value → bypass checks, unlock features}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Where can I redirect execution?}}
\li{Existing code: system(), exec(), one_gadget}
\li{Leaked addresses: libc functions}
\li{Injected code: shellcode (if DEP/NX disabled)}
\li{ROP chains: reuse existing code fragments}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{How do I read the flag?}}
\li{Direct: Call system("/bin/cat flag.txt") or open()/read()/write()}
\li{Shell: Call system("/bin/sh") and interact}
\li{Leak: Read flag into buffer, leak buffer contents}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Methodologies}
\subtree{
\title{Vulnerability Discovery}
\p{\strong{Unsafe API Pattern Recognition:}}

\p{Identify dangerous functions that don't enforce bounds:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Unbounded copies}: strcpy, strcat, sprintf, gets}
\li{\startverb **Underspecified bounds**: read(), recv(), scanf("%s"), strncpy (no null termination)\stopverb}
\li{\strong{Format string bugs}: printf(user_input), fprintf(fp, user_input)}
\li{\strong{Integer overflows}: malloc(user_size), buffer[user_index], length calculations}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation strategy:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-symbols\stopverb} includeExternal=true → Find unsafe API imports}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} to unsafe functions → Locate usage points}
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} with includeContext=true → Analyze calling context}
\li{Trace data flow from input to unsafe operation}
}

\p{\strong{Stack Layout Analysis:}}

\p{Understand memory organization:}

\pre{\startverb
High addresses
├── Function arguments
├── Return address         ← Critical target for overflow
├── Saved frame pointer
├── Local variables        ← Vulnerable buffers here
├── Compiler canaries      ← Stack protection (if enabled)
└── Padding/alignment
Low addresses
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Investigation strategy:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} of vulnerable function → See local variable layout}
\li{Estimate offsets: buffer → saved registers → return address}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Analysis" category="Vulnerability" at overflow site}
\li{\code{\startverb set-decompilation-comment\stopverb} documenting buffer size and adjacent targets}
}

\p{\strong{Heap Exploitation Patterns:}}

\p{Heap vulnerabilities differ from stack:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Use-after-free}: Access freed memory (dangling pointers)}
\li{\strong{Double-free}: Free same memory twice (corrupt allocator metadata)}
\li{\strong{Heap overflow}: Overflow into adjacent heap chunk (overwrite metadata/data)}
\li{\strong{Type confusion}: Use object as wrong type after reallocation}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation strategy:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="(malloc|free|realloc)" → Find heap operations}
\li{Trace pointer lifecycle: allocation → use → free}
\li{Look for dangling pointer usage after free}
\li{Identify adjacent allocations (overflow targets)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Memory Layout Understanding}
\p{\strong{Address Space Discovery:}}

\p{Map the binary's memory:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-memory-blocks\stopverb} → See sections (.text, .data, .bss, heap, stack)}
\li{Note executable sections (shellcode candidates if NX disabled)}
\li{Note writable sections (data corruption targets)}
\li{Identify ASLR status (addresses randomized each run?)}
}

\p{\strong{Offsets and Distances:}}

\p{Calculate critical distances:}

\ul{
\li{Buffer to return address: For stack overflow payload sizing}
\li{GOT to PLT: For GOT overwrite attacks}
\li{Heap chunk to chunk: For heap overflow targeting}
\li{libc base to useful functions: For address calculation after leak}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation strategy:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-data\stopverb} or \code{\startverb read-memory\stopverb} at known addresses → Sample memory layout}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} direction="both" → Map relationships}
\li{Calculate offsets manually from decompilation}
\li{\code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb} at key offsets documenting distances}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Exploitation Planning}
\p{\strong{Constraint Analysis:}}

\p{Identify exploitation constraints:}

\ul{
\li{\startverb **Bad bytes**: Null bytes (\x00) terminate C strings → avoid in address/payload\stopverb}
\li{\strong{Input size limits}: Truncation, buffering, network MTU}
\li{\strong{Character restrictions}: Printable-only, alphanumeric, no special chars}
\li{\strong{Protection mechanisms}: Detect via \code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="(canary|__stack_chk)"}
}

\p{\strong{Bypass Strategies:}}

\p{Common protections and bypass techniques:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Stack canaries}: Leak canary value, brute-force (fork servers), overwrite without corrupting}
\li{\strong{ASLR}: Leak addresses (format strings, uninitialized data), partial overwrite (last byte randomization)}
\li{\strong{NX/DEP}: ROP (Return-Oriented Programming), ret2libc, JOP (Jump-Oriented Programming)}
\li{\strong{PIE}: Leak code addresses, relative offsets within binary, partial overwrites}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation Primitives:}}

\p{Build these fundamental capabilities:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Arbitrary write}: Write controlled data to chosen address (format string, heap overflow)}
\li{\strong{Arbitrary read}: Read from chosen address (format string, uninitialized data, overflow into pointer)}
\li{\strong{Control flow hijack}: Redirect execution (overwrite return address, function pointer, GOT entry)}
\li{\strong{Information leak}: Obtain addresses, canaries, pointers (uninitialized variables, format strings)}
}

\p{\strong{Chain multiple primitives when needed:}}

\ul{
\li{Leak → Calculate addresses → Overwrite function pointer → Exploit}
\li{Partial overwrite → Leak full address → Calculate libc base → ret2libc}
\li{Heap overflow → Overwrite function pointer → Arbitrary write → GOT overwrite → Shell}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Flexible Workflow}
\p{This is a \strong{thinking framework}, not a rigid checklist. Adapt to the challenge:}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 1: Binary Reconnaissance (5-10 tool calls)}
\p{\strong{Understand the challenge:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-current-program\stopverb} or \code{\startverb list-project-files\stopverb} → Identify target binary}
\li{\code{\startverb get-memory-blocks\stopverb} → Map sections, identify protections}
\li{\code{\startverb get-functions\stopverb} filterDefaultNames=false → Count functions (stripped vs. symbolic)}
\li{\code{\startverb get-strings\stopverb} regexPattern="flag" → Find flag-related strings}
\li{\code{\startverb get-symbols\stopverb} includeExternal=true → List imported functions}
}

\p{\strong{Identify entry points and input vectors:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} functionNameOrAddress="main" limit=50 → See program flow}
\li{Look for input functions: read(), recv(), gets(), scanf(), fgets()}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} to input functions → Map input flow}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="TODO" category="Input Vector" at each input point}
}

\p{\strong{Flag suspicious patterns:}}

\ul{
\li{Unsafe functions (strcpy, sprintf, gets)}
\li{Large stack buffers with small read operations}
\li{Format string vulnerabilities (user-controlled format)}
\li{Unbounded loops or recursion}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Vulnerability Analysis (10-15 tool calls)}
\p{\strong{Trace data flow from input to vulnerability:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} of input-handling function with includeReferenceContext=true}
\li{Identify buffer sizes: char buf[64], malloc(size), etc.}
\li{Identify write operations: strcpy(dest, src), read(fd, buf, 1024)}
\li{\strong{Calculate vulnerability}: Write size > buffer size?}
}

\p{\strong{Analyze vulnerable function context:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb rename-variables\stopverb} → Clarify data flow (user_input, buffer, size, etc.)}
\li{\code{\startverb change-variable-datatypes\stopverb} → Fix types for clarity}
\li{\code{\startverb set-decompilation-comment\stopverb} → Document vulnerability location and type}
}

\p{\strong{Map memory layout around vulnerability:}}

\ol{
\li{Identify local variables and their stack positions}
\li{Calculate offset from buffer start to return address}
\li{\code{\startverb read-memory\stopverb} at nearby addresses → Sample stack layout (if debugging available)}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Overflow" → Mark vulnerability}
}

\p{\strong{Cross-reference analysis:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} to vulnerable function → How is it called?}
\li{Check for exploitation helpers: system(), exec(), "/bin/sh" string}
\li{\code{\startverb get-strings\stopverb} regexPattern="/bin/(sh|bash)" → Find shell strings}
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="system|exec" → Find execution functions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Exploitation Strategy (5-10 tool calls)}
\p{\strong{Determine exploitation approach:}}

\p{Based on protections and available primitives:}

\p{\strong{If no protections (NX disabled, no canary, no ASLR):}}

\ul{
\li{Stack overflow → overwrite return address → jump to shellcode}
\li{Inject shellcode in buffer, jump to buffer address}
}

\p{\strong{If NX enabled but no ASLR:}}

\ul{
\li{ret2libc: Overwrite return address → chain to system() with "/bin/sh"}
\li{ROP chain: Chain gadgets to build system("/bin/sh") call}
\li{GOT overwrite: Overwrite GOT entry to redirect library call}
}

\p{\strong{If ASLR enabled:}}

\ul{
\li{Leak addresses first (format string, uninitialized data)}
\li{Calculate libc base from leaked address}
\li{Use leak to build ROP chain or ret2libc with correct addresses}
}

\p{\strong{If stack canary present:}}

\ul{
\li{Leak canary value (format string, sequential overflow)}
\li{Preserve canary in overflow payload}
\li{Or use heap exploitation instead}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation for each strategy:}}

\ol{
\li{\startverb `get-strings` regexPattern="(\\x2f|/)bin/(sh|bash)" → Find shell strings\stopverb}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} to "/bin/sh" → Get string address}
\li{\code{\startverb get-symbols\stopverb} includeExternal=true → Find system/exec imports}
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} of system → Get address (if not PIE)}
}

\p{\strong{For ROP:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="(pop|ret)" → Find gadget candidates}
\li{Manual ROP gadget discovery (use external tools like ROPgadget)}
\li{Document gadget addresses with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Note" category="ROP Gadget"}
}

\p{\strong{For format string exploitation:}}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} of printf call → Analyze format string control}
\li{\startverb Test format string primitives: %x (leak), %n (write), %s (arbitrary read)\stopverb}
\li{\code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb} documenting exploitation primitive}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Payload Construction (Conceptual)}
\p{\strong{Build the exploit payload:}}

\p{This happens \strong{outside Ghidra} using Python/pwntools, but plan it here:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Document payload structure} using \code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb}:}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Record critical addresses} with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb}:}
\li{Buffer address: 0x7fffffffdd00}
\li{Return address location: 0x7fffffffdd40 (offset +64)}
\li{system() address: 0x7ffff7e14410}
\li{"/bin/sh" string: 0x00404030}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Document exploitation steps} with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Analysis" category="Exploit Plan":}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Track assumptions} with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Assumption":}
\li{"Assuming stack addresses are stable (no ASLR)"}
\li{"Assuming no canary based on decompilation (verify runtime)"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 5: Exploitation Validation (Iterative)}
\p{\strong{This phase happens outside Ghidra}, but document findings:}

\ol{
\li{Test exploit against local binary}
\li{Adjust offsets based on crash analysis}
\li{Handle bad bytes or character restrictions}
\li{Refine payload until successful}
}

\p{\strong{Update Ghidra database with findings:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb} with actual working offsets}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} documenting successful exploitation}
\li{\code{\startverb checkin-program\stopverb} message="Documented successful exploitation of buffer overflow in function_X"}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Pattern Recognition}
\p{See \code{\startverb patterns.md\stopverb} for detailed vulnerability patterns:}

\ul{
\li{Unsafe API usage patterns}
\li{Buffer overflow indicators}
\li{Format string vulnerability signatures}
\li{Heap exploitation patterns}
\li{Integer overflow scenarios}
\li{Control flow hijacking opportunities}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Exploitation Techniques Reference}
\subtree{
\title{Stack Buffer Overflow}
\p{\strong{Concept}: Write beyond buffer bounds to overwrite return address or function pointers on stack.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{\startverb Find unsafe copy: strcpy, gets, scanf("%s"), read with large size\stopverb}
\li{Identify buffer size from decompilation}
\li{Compare buffer size to maximum input size}
\li{Calculate offset to return address (buffer size + saved registers)}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation}:}

\ul{
\li{Payload: [padding to return address] + [new return address] + [optional arguments/ROP chain]}
\li{Target: Overwrite return address to redirect execution}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Format String Vulnerability}
\p{\strong{Concept}: User-controlled format string allows arbitrary memory read/write.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="printf|fprintf|sprintf"}
\li{Check if format string comes from user input: printf(user_buffer)}
\li{\startverb Vulnerable pattern: printf(input) instead of printf("%s", input)\stopverb}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation}:}

\ul{
\li{\startverb Read: %x, %p (leak stack values), %s (arbitrary read via pointer on stack)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Write: %n (write number of bytes printed to pointer on stack)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Position: %N$x (access Nth argument directly)\stopverb}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} with includeReferenceContext → See printf call context}
\li{\code{\startverb set-decompilation-comment\stopverb} documenting format string control}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Format String"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Return-Oriented Programming (ROP)}
\p{\strong{Concept}: Chain existing code fragments (gadgets) ending in 'ret' to build arbitrary computation without injecting code.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{Find gadgets: \code{\startverb pop reg; ret\stopverb}, \code{\startverb mov [addr], reg; ret\stopverb}, \code{\startverb syscall; ret\stopverb}}
\li{External tool: ROPgadget, ropper (Ghidra doesn't have built-in gadget search)}
\li{Document gadgets in Ghidra with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Note" category="ROP Gadget"}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation}:}

\ul{
\li{Chain gadgets by placing addresses on stack}
\li{Each gadget executes, then 'ret' pops next gadget address}
\li{Build syscall with proper registers: execve("/bin/sh", NULL, NULL)}
}

\p{\strong{Workflow}:}

\ol{
\li{Identify required gadgets for goal (e.g., execve syscall)}
\li{\code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb} at gadget addresses documenting purpose}
\li{Plan ROP chain structure with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Analysis" category="ROP Chain"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{ret2libc}
\p{\strong{Concept}: Redirect execution to libc functions (system, exec, one_gadget) instead of shellcode.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-symbols\stopverb} includeExternal=true → Find libc imports}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} to system, execve → Get addresses}
\li{\code{\startverb get-strings\stopverb} regexPattern="/bin/sh" → Find shell string}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation} (no ASLR):}

\ul{
\li{Overwrite return address → system function address}
\li{Set first argument → pointer to "/bin/sh" string}
\li{Calling convention: x86-64 uses RDI for first arg, x86 uses stack}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation} (with ASLR):}

\ul{
\li{Leak libc address (format string, uninitialized pointer)}
\li{Calculate system/exec address = libc_base + offset}
\li{Build ROP chain with calculated addresses}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb get-data\stopverb} at GOT entries → See libc function addresses}
\li{Calculate libc base from known offset}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} documenting calculated addresses}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Heap Exploitation}
\p{\strong{Concept}: Corrupt heap metadata or overflow between heap chunks to achieve arbitrary write or control flow hijack.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} pattern="malloc|free|realloc"}
\li{Trace allocation and free patterns}
\li{Look for use-after-free: pointer used after free()}
\li{Look for heap overflow: write beyond allocated size}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation techniques}:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Use-after-free}: Free object, allocate new object in same slot, use old pointer to access new object (type confusion)}
\li{\strong{Double-free}: Free same pointer twice, corrupt allocator metadata}
\li{\strong{Heap overflow}: Overflow into next chunk, overwrite metadata (size, pointers) or data (function pointers)}
\li{\strong{Fastbin/tcache poisoning}: Corrupt freelist pointers to allocate arbitrary memory}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb rename-variables\stopverb} for heap pointers (heap_ptr, freed_ptr, chunk1, chunk2)}
\li{\code{\startverb set-decompilation-comment\stopverb} at allocation/free sites}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Use-After-Free"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integer Overflow}
\p{\strong{Concept}: Integer overflow/underflow leads to incorrect buffer size calculation or bounds check bypass.}

\p{\strong{Discovery}:}

\ol{
\li{Find size calculations: size = user_input * sizeof(element)}
\li{Check for overflow: What if user_input is very large?}
\li{Find bounds checks: if (index < size) → What if index is large unsigned?}
}

\p{\strong{Exploitation}:}

\ul{
\li{Overflow allocation size → heap buffer too small → heap overflow}
\li{Underflow size check → negative check bypassed → buffer overflow}
\li{Wrap-around arithmetic → bypass length checks}
}

\p{\strong{Investigation}:}

\ol{
\li{\code{\startverb change-variable-datatypes\stopverb} to proper integer types (uint32_t, size_t)}
\li{Identify overflow scenarios in comments}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Integer Overflow"}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tool Integration}
\p{\strong{Use ReVa tools systematically:}}

\subtree{
\title{Discovery Tools}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb get-symbols\stopverb} → Find unsafe API imports}
\li{\code{\startverb get-strings\stopverb} → Find interesting strings (flag, shell, paths)}
\li{\code{\startverb search-decompilation\stopverb} → Find vulnerability patterns (unsafe functions)}
\li{\code{\startverb get-functions-by-similarity\stopverb} → Find functions similar to known vulnerable pattern}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analysis Tools}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb get-decompilation\stopverb} with \code{\startverb includeIncomingReferences=true\stopverb} and \code{\startverb includeReferenceContext=true\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb find-cross-references\stopverb} with \code{\startverb includeContext=true\stopverb} → Trace data flow}
\li{\code{\startverb get-data\stopverb} → Examine global variables, GOT entries, constant data}
\li{\code{\startverb read-memory\stopverb} → Sample memory layout}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Database Improvement Tools}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb rename-variables\stopverb} → Clarify exploitation-relevant variables (buffer, user_input, return_addr)}
\li{\code{\startverb change-variable-datatypes\stopverb} → Fix types for proper understanding}
\li{\code{\startverb set-decompilation-comment\stopverb} → Document vulnerabilities inline}
\li{\code{\startverb set-comment\stopverb} → Document exploitation strategy at key addresses}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} → Track vulnerabilities, gadgets, exploit plan}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Organization Tools}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning" category="Vulnerability" → Mark vulnerabilities}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Note" category="ROP Gadget" → Track gadgets}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Analysis" category="Exploit Plan" → Document strategy}
\li{\code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="TODO" category="Verify" → Track assumptions to verify}
\li{\code{\startverb checkin-program\stopverb} → Save progress}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Success Criteria}
\p{You've successfully completed the challenge when:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Vulnerability identified}: Specific function, line, and vulnerability type documented}
\li{\strong{Memory layout understood}: Buffer sizes, offsets, adjacent data mapped}
\li{\strong{Exploitation strategy planned}: Clear path from vulnerability to flag documented}
\li{\strong{Critical addresses recorded}: All addresses needed for exploit payload documented}
\li{\strong{Assumptions tracked}: All assumptions documented with confidence levels}
\li{\strong{Database improved}: Renamed variables, added comments, set bookmarks for clarity}
\li{\strong{Exploit plan ready}: Sufficient information to write exploit code outside Ghidra}
}

\p{\strong{Return to user:}}

\ul{
\li{Vulnerability description with evidence}
\li{Exploitation approach explanation}
\li{Critical addresses and offsets}
\li{Payload structure plan}
\li{Assumptions and verification needs}
\li{Follow-up tasks if needed (e.g., "Test exploit against binary")}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Anti-Patterns}
\p{\strong{Don't}:}

\ul{
\li{Assume vulnerability without evidence (check buffer sizes!)}
\li{Forget about protections (canaries, NX, ASLR, PIE)}
\li{Overlook input restrictions (bad bytes, size limits)}
\li{Get stuck on one approach (try different exploitation techniques)}
\li{Ignore calling conventions (x86 vs x64 argument passing)}
\li{Forget null byte termination (C string functions)}
}

\p{\strong{Do}:}

\ul{
\li{Verify buffer sizes from decompilation}
\li{Check for stack canaries: \code{\startverb __stack_chk_fail\stopverb} references}
\li{Calculate offsets precisely (buffer to return address)}
\li{Document all assumptions with \code{\startverb set-bookmark\stopverb} type="Warning"}
\li{Adapt exploitation technique to protections present}
\li{Think creatively (chain primitives, use unconventional targets)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Remember}
\p{Binary exploitation is \strong{creative problem-solving}:}

\ul{
\li{Understand \strong{why} vulnerabilities exist (unsafe assumptions)}
\li{Think \strong{how} to manipulate memory (data flow analysis)}
\li{Plan \strong{what} to overwrite (control flow, data, pointers)}
\li{Determine \strong{where} to redirect (existing code, injected code, ROP)}
\li{Execute \strong{step-by-step} (leak, calculate, overwrite, trigger)}
}

\p{Every CTF challenge is different. Use this framework to \strong{think} about exploitation, not as a checklist to blindly follow.}

\p{\strong{Your goal}: Document enough information in Ghidra to write the exploit script. The actual exploitation happens outside, but the analysis happens here.}
}
}